<subSubSection lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="45" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="45.[667,1194,1557,1759]" lastBlockId="46.[701,1228,1384,1759]" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="45" pageNumber="48">
DIAGNOSIS: Recognized by the presence of discrete small dark spots on the dorsum (pl. 3), and the structure of the male genitalia, the left paramere with a somewhat elongate, apex positioned somewhat asymmetrically and the posterolateral shoulder with a low projection; endosoma with a weakly elongate, condensed grouping of heavy denticles on the postgonoporal portion of the secondary strap and recurved ventral process associated with the secondary gonopore. Most easily confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schuh &amp; C. Weirauch" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Melaleucoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leuropomae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="49">M. leuropomae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the form of the spots and the structure of the male genitalia, but the spots in that species usually smaller, the apical medial process of the left paramere more strongly asymmetrical, and the row of denticles on the secondary endosomal strap longer, with the denticles more evenly spaced. Spots on the dorsum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schuh &amp; C. Weirauch" authorityYear="2010" box="[471,654,1736,1759]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Melaleucoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beaufortiae">
<emphasis box="[471,654,1736,1759]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="49">M. beaufortiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
always somewhat coalescent and those in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schuh &amp; C. Weirauch" authorityYear="2010" box="[701,867,1413,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Melaleucoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevifoliae">
<emphasis box="[701,867,1413,1435]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="49">M. brevifoliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tiny and much more numerous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption box="[276,1080,1315,1335]" pageId="46" pageNumber="49" startId="46.[276,314,1316,1335]" targetBox="[131,1224,211,1275]" targetPageId="46">
<paragraph blockId="46.[276,1080,1315,1335]" box="[276,1080,1315,1335]" pageId="46" pageNumber="49">
